  {id:84,title:`Pharma Giant Acquisition – M&A Interview`,type:`M&A`,difficulty:`Challenging`,content:`M&A | Pharma Sector | Challenging\nPharma Giant’s Acquisition\nYour client is a CEO of a global pharma company. The client has an offer to buy the patent and selling right for a newly developed drug that cures balding. It\nwants youto analysetheacquisition dilemma and giverecommendations.\nInterviewee Notes Approach/ Framework\n• It is important to understand Acquire the new drug ?\nthe objectives and\nInternal\nconstraints of the client\n• Enquire about both the Market Financial Technical due Operational Risks and\nSynergies & fit\nacquirer and the acquiring attractiveness attractiveness diligence feasibility benefits\ncompany and understand the\nExternal\nproduct mix, geography, type\nof integration across supply\nchain, competitors. Market Size co E m x p is e t t i i n t g o rs p G o r t o e w nt t i h al C t l r in ia ic ls al Setup plant M di a s r tr k i e b t u in ti g o n &\n• It is convenient to structure\nat each step instead of laying\nFair value < $ 2 Mn NPV = 2 Mn (Tax = 50%)\ndown a laundry list of things. Bald people\nNo treatment:\n• Make use of formulas. globally\nWigs, caps\n• Assume all the values are\nExpected Revenues Expected Cost = FC+ VC\nmentioned as the present Fraction opting = 0.1*0.2*0.4*3 Bn = 24 Mn = (8+4+4+4) = 20 Mn\nfor treatments\nvalues. Therefore, ignore the\nTreatment\ntime value of money.\nMarketing &\nFraction opting Expected cost of Other Fixed costs Variable cost\nDistribution cost\nfor drugs Clinical trials 4M 4M\nEvasive 4M\nMarket share of 0.1 Phase II 0.2 Phase III 0.4 4Mn +\nour drug Non-Evasive 0.1*20Mn +\n20 Mn 100 Mn\n0.1*0.2*100Mn\nUsage Frequency Phase I = 8 Mn\nTraditional\n4 Mn\n0.9 Phase 1 0.8 Phase II 0.6\nPrice of our Non- Phase III failure\nfailure failure\ndrug Traditional\nRecommendations\n• Short term: a) Do a through technical due diligence of the drug by using the expertise of company researchers.\nb) Plan and expedite the process of clinical trials to get timely approvals for rolling out the drug globally.\n• Long term: a) Leverage the technical expertise to ensure the drug quality and leverage the existing distribution network of thecompany with direct promotional strategies directly to the consumer.\nb) The plant’s equipment can be salvaged as the demand for the drug will drop due to its one-time usage, therefore get rid of excess capacity.\nKey Learnings\n• It is important in cases like this to be comprehensive, and hence bucketing the problems into different sections helps in structured thinking.\n• Beware of calculation`},
  {id:85,title:`BPO COMPANY`,type:`M&A`,difficulty:`Moderate`,content:`BPO COMPANY\nRight. The clients are moving to our competitors. The clients in Europe\ndesire integrated services and our competitors are selling a bundle of\nconsulting, IT and BPO services, whereas we offer only BPO services. We\nwant to improve our revenues in the next 6 months. What should wedo?\nSetting up our own consulting and IT verticals won’t be possible in the given\ntimeline. Hence, we can explore M&A with some local firms offering these\nservices, which will bring in their clients and complement our BPO services.\nLocal firms will have local sales-personnel who’d help us understand the\nlocal landscape and help in better conversion. If closing an M&A in such a\nshort-term is not possible, we can develop a revenue sharing agreement\nwith firms that offer the require services and try to offer a combined service\nto the client\nGreat. We can close the case here. Thank you!\n71`},
  {id:86,title:`Market Entry - Case Structure `,type:`M&A`,difficulty:`Moderate`,content:`Market Entry - Case Structure \nA global investment bank wants to enter India. Help it out.\nQualitative Information Case Framework Quantitative Data & Analysis\nCase background: Expected 1 year revenue:\nUS based top 20 global IB entering India Number of deals by product:\ninvestment bank wants to\nM&A:\nenter Indian due to slow-\nExpected market\ndown of US/European Indian market Product DCM M&A ECM\nshare and key Mode of entry\nconditions\nmarkets financial metrics\nNo. of\n4 3 10\nDeals\nMacroeconomic IB industry Product-wise Financial\nDirect Entry JV/Acquisition\nfactors factors market share Projections Average\n2 5 1\nsize ($bn)\nCase facts:\n10 year growth Average margins Expected share Revenue and cost On-shore/Off- Niche player\nFour products: DCM, ECM, rate and deal sizes and projections projections shore operations acquisition Margin 3% 5% 2%\nFX, M&A\nKey customers: Fortune 1000 Revenue break-\nNumber of Banking ROE and break- Partnership with\nup by each Revenues=\nfirms, other multimillion $ metros regulations even analysis local bank\nproduct\nfirms and HNIs\n4*2*0.03+3*5*0.05+\nNumber of IB growth rate in Synergy with 10*1*0.02bn.$\nRisk ratios-vary,\nHNIs/Multi-Mn$ India vs other bank’s current\nCar, Capital ratios\nfirms markets market portfolio = $1.19bn\nProblems and recommendations Interviewee feedback\nSince we discussed the factors that will drive entry into the market, we can say that Though the case statement may appear complicated and might give the impression\nthe decision will be contingent on the result of the proposed analysis in the case. that a knowledge of Investment banking industry is required, the fundamental\nRecommendation: Conduct the mentioned analysis quickly to converge to a mechanics of the case is very simple. Probing the interviewer with right set of\ndecision questions and ability to handle difficult jargons can be very useful.\n`}